    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-21T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-21T11:00:00-05:00" n="456"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d456">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">656.56D/12–2151: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Trimble</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-21T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 21, 1951—5 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>627. 1. Retiring Brit Amb<note n="1" xml:id="d456fn1">Sir Philip B. B.
                        Nichols.</note> told me that during farewell call on <gloss
                        target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> yesterday Drees had appeared most
                    pessimistic re current <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> Neth discussions.
                    Latter had expressed opinion that <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss>s
                    apparently not desirous reaching settlement as indicated by fact <gloss
                        target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> del constantly “shifting their position”.
                    Drees also said Supomo seemingly has no authority to take any decision even of
                    minor nature and must consult Djakarta on every move.</p>
                <p>2. During dinner my house two days ago, SecGen <gloss target="#t_PriMin1"
                        >PriMin</gloss> office,<note n="2" xml:id="d456fn2">C. L. W. Fock.</note>
                    who is also member of Dutch del said he was not concerned about any arrangements
                    which might be entered into re union statute since <gloss target="#t_Indo1"
                        >Indo</gloss> probably would not observe them in any case and in support
                    this view asserted that <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> had failed to live
                    up to “80 percent” of commitments given <gloss target="#t_RTC1">RTC</gloss>
                    agreement. On other hand, he as member of Neth del, would strongly oppose any
                    attempt to transfer sovereignty over <gloss target="#t_NNG1">NNG</gloss> to RI,
                    at this time.</p>
                <p>3. Austral Amb who saw Stikker Dec 19, said latter far less optimistic than Blom
                    that <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> would refrain unilateral denunciation
                    union statute (<gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 619 Dec 19). Stikker
                    also informed him that <gloss target="#t_Indo1">Indo</gloss> del had been put on
                    notice that substance of discussions could not commence until instances referred
                    to in <gloss target="#t_reftel1">reftel</gloss> had been satisfactorily
                    settled.</p>
                <pb facs="0784" n="766" xml:id="pg_766"/>
                <p>Dept pass Djakarta, sent Dept 627, rptd info Paris 122, Djakarta 3, London 153,
                    Canberra unn.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Trimble</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
